The passage is **Chapter 13** of `charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2`. The chapter title is itself the answer: *"Distinction entre un régime arbitraire et un régime légal."*

Comte's distinction turns entirely on whether the exercise of power has been **described in advance**:

- **Arbitrary/despotic regime**: power acts without prior description — irregular, variable, disordered (like a steam engine without a regulator).
- **Legal regime**: the action of power has been described beforehand — it acts uniformly and equally in all similar cases.

His critical twist (p-fadb97, p-9f5b65): this difference is *only* one of regularity, not goodness. A legal regime can be just as oppressive as a despotic one — "one can put regularity into pillage." The real question is not whether one is subject to law, but whether one is subject to *good* law.
